\begin_layout Title
Increase in the Mortality Rates of African-American Women in the Aftermath
 of Mandatory Arrest Laws:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

A Study in Unintended Effects
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Sinan Ozel
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

University of Victoria
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
From the late 1970s into the 1990s, 20 states in the USA passed 'mandatory
 arrest laws', designed to curb domestic violence, by requiring the responding
 officer to arrest the offender.
 I show that these laws led to an increase in the mortality rates of African-Ame
rican women.
 The increase takes place three to five years after the law has been passed
 and loses its statistical significance as time passes.
 I infer from these results that mandatory arrest laws had unintended consequenc
es for the victims whose partners were arrested, but that these unintended
 consequences impacted the victims only in the few years following the law.
 I conclude that increased awareness of the law and offender deterrence
 eventually mitigates these unintended consequences.
\end_layout

