\begin_layout Standard
In the current paper, I present evidence that mandatory arrest laws, intended
 to protect victims of domestic violence, led to a temporary increase in
 the mortality rates of African-American women.
 While this result may seem unexpected at first, prior literature suggests
 that such an outcome is possible: in an experimental setting, African-American
 victims were twice as likely to be dead after 23 years if their offending
 partners are arrested 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "sherman2014increased"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 If arresting a domestic violence offender can unintentionally increase
 the probability of death for a victim, then mandating arrest as a policy
 for domestic violence can also unintentionally increase mortality rates
 of African-American women.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main purpose and contribution of this paper is to estimate the impact
 of mandatory arrest laws on mortality rates of African-American women.
 For this purpose, I construct a data set of yearly mortality rates by state,
 gender and race.
 Results from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "sherman2014increased"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 suggest that victim mortality increases with partner arrest, but this result
 is limited to an experimental setting where the deterrence effects of the
 new law are non-existent or limited: offenders were not aware that their
 actions could lead to an arrest, and could not have been deterred from
 committing violence in the first place.
 Outside of the experiment, once the mandatory arrest laws are passed and
 known by the population, potential offenders can be deterred from offending
 in the first place.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the identification of effects, I exploit the variation in the timing
 of the passing of the mandatory arrest laws.
 For this purpose, I use two empirical specifications: a difference-in-differenc
es model and a fixed effects model.
 The difference-in-differences model is the standard approach in identifying
 causal impacts.
 Fixed effects models are a generalization of the difference-in-differences
 models and have been used in difference-in-differences settings.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "lovenheim_long-run_2019,anderson_does_2015,huebener_compressing_2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 With the fixed effects model in the current paper, I am able control for
 state-specific confounding factors, and confounding factors specific to
 each year.
 Furthermore, I am able to control for linear time trends peculiar to each
 state, as suggested by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "angrist_mostly_2008"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, with the fixed-effects model, I am able to estimate the timing
 of the impact.
 In both specifications, I find a statistically significant increase in
 mortality rates of African-American women.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main identification assumption for the difference-in-differences model
 requires mortality rates in control and mandatory to follow similar trends.
 I present the trends in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:trends"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The identification assumption for the fixed effects model requires the
 timing of the laws to be independent of confounding factors and the outcome
 variable.
 These confounding factors may come from data that is not observed or collected.
 To control for the unobserved confounding factors that are specific to
 a state, state-fixed controls are included in the model, and to control
 for the confounding factors that are common across all states but vary
 over time, year-fixed controls are included.
 What remains are factors that may be correlated to a particular timing
 of the law passing in a given state.
 In the current setting, it was nation-wide events, and not state-specific
 triggers, that led to the passing of the laws 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "iyengar2009doesthe,buzawa1996doarrests"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 This increases my confidence that the identification assumptions are met.
 In spite of this, I also include state-year economic, demographic and political
 controls, as well as state-specific linear time trends.
 The results remain statistically significant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This paper has two main results: mandatory arrest laws led to an unintentional
 increase in the mortality rates of African-American women, and this increase
 was temporary.
 I interpret these results as the consequence of deterrence of partners
 by mandatory arrest.
 The mandatory arrest laws created unintended consequences for the victims
 in the first couple of years after they were passed, but in the following
 years, they helped the victims by deterring the offenders, an effect that
 was not captured in the experimental setting by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "sherman2014increased"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 I discuss possible mechanisms and alternative explanations in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:discussion"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The rest of the paper is organized as follows.
 In Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:mal-background"

\end_inset

, I give the background information regarding mandatory arrest laws, the
 social experiments regarding spousal arrest, and a brief review of the
 literature concerning mandatory arrest laws.
 In Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:mal-data"

\end_inset

, I explain the construction of the data set used for the analysis.
 In Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:mal-methodology"

\end_inset

, I explain my methodology.
 In Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:mal-results"

\end_inset

, I demonstrate that there is an impact of the mandatory arrest laws on
 the mortality rate of African-American women, and that this impact was
 not sustained in the long run.
 Finally, in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:conclusions"

\end_inset

