\begin_layout Standard
Around the same time that mandatory arrest laws were being passed, the results
 from MDVE were challenged by a series of experiments.
 These experiments are collectively called the Spouse Arrest Replication
 Program, or SARP.
 For the most part, the SARP replication experiments do not confirm the
 original findings from MDVE 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "sherman1992thevariable,maxwell2001theeffects,berk1992thedeterrent"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Despite this rejection, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "berk1992thedeterrent"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 show that there is a decrease in repeated offense for offenders with a
 strong 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

stake in society
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, for instance, employed offenders.
 Finally, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "maxwell2002thepreventive"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 conduct a meta study combining all experiments from the SARP program.
 They conclude that arrest does in fact reduce repeated offense.
 They also confirm the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

stake in society
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 argument by showing that the decrease is larger for employed offenders.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The largest of these replication experiments was the Milwaukee Domestic
 Violence Experiment (MilDVE).
 Recently, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "sherman2014increased"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 conducted a follow-up study on the victims 23 years after the experiment.
 Surprisingly, they found that spouses of offenders who were arrested were
 twice as likely to be dead.
 It is not clear what causes the deaths, and it is also not clear how long
 after the arrest the deaths take place.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Even though 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "sherman2014increased"
literal "true"

\end_inset

