\begin_layout Standard
To identify the effect of mandatory and recommended arrest laws on the mortality
 rates of African-American women, I exploit the fact that the laws passed
 in different years in different states.
 For identification, I employ a difference-in-differences strategy and implement
 this strategy in two baseline models.
 The first model is the classic difference-in-differences model:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y_{s,t}=\beta_{0}+\beta_{1}T_{s,t}+\beta_{2}T_{s}+\beta_{3}T_{t}+\epsilon_{s,t}\label{eq:did-model}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$ 
\backslash
beta_1 $
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is the coefficient of interest.Correspondingly, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$ T_{s,t} $
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is a binary variable that takes the value 1 if a state 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$s$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 has already passed the mandatory or recommended arrest law passed in a
 given year 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$t$
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The binary variable 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$ T_s $
\end_layout

\end_inset

 takes the value 1 if a state 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$s$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 ever passes a mandatory or recommended arrest law.
 The binary variable 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$ T_t $
\end_layout

\end_inset

 takes the value 0 in the years before the passing of an arrest law, and
 the value 1 in the years after passing of an arrest law, for all states.
 The setting is different from a traditional difference-in-differences setting
 in the sense that before and after are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

staggered
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, or different for each state.
 Because mortality rates are not stable over time, I only include four years
 before and after the law passing.
