\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second model is a fixed-effects model.
 This allows me to exploit the variation in passing of the laws across states
 and over time by including state-fixed effects and year-fixed effects.
 This model controls for everything that the difference-in-differences model
 controls for, but allows the states to vary in their unobserved characteristics.
 It also allows me to control for unobserved characteristics specific to
 each year.
 The baseline estimation equation is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y_{s,t}=\beta_{m}M_{s,t}+\psi X_{s,t}+\alpha_{s}+\lambda_{t}+\epsilon_{s,t}\label{eq:static-model}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, the subscripts 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$ s $
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$ t $
\end_layout

\end_inset

 denote state and year.
 Correspondingly, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$ 
\backslash
alpha_s $
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$ 
\backslash
lambda_t $
\end_layout

\end_inset

 refer to the set of binary variables that control unobservable factors
 particular to each state, and unobservable factors that change over time
 across all states.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$ 
\backslash
beta_m $
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is the effect of mandatory or recommended arrest laws on mortality rates.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$ M_{s,t} $
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is a binary variable denoting whether a mandatory or a recommended arrest
 law is in effect in a given state and year.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$ X_{s,t} $
\end_layout

\end_inset

